Asturias to less studied intellectuals such as Wingston González and Carl Rigby. The result is a fresh approach to race, the region, and its literature. Black in Print understands Central American Blackness as a set of shifting coordinates plotted on the axes of language, geography, and time as it moves through print media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexPress coveragezCentral America. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCentral America. 0aRace relations and the presszCentral America. 4aAfrican American Studies : Black Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849283440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438492834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438492834/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles